      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so i was reading about space stuff and i dont really get what a planetary conjunction actually is. like do they actually hit each other or im just seeing them close together from earth? also how does orbital inclination play into how close they look?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A planetary conjunction occurs when multiple celestial bodies, typically planets, appear close together in the sky, but they don't actually touch or collide with each other. This happens when Earth passes between two or more planets or other celestial bodies at a specific point in their orbits. The apparent closeness of these bodies is an optical illusion due to the positioning of Earth and the observer's perspective. Orbital inclination plays a role in the apparent closeness, as a closer inclination between Earth and the other bodies can make them appear more overlapping in the sky.",
