    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if two planets have really different orbital inclinations, does that mean they'll usually look pretty far apart even if they're technically in \"conjunction\"? like, is there a way to predict how much they'll actually look like they're touching?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the difference in orbital inclinations between two planets can affect how close they appear in conjunction. Because their orbits are tilted relative to each other, the apparent separation of the planets will be smaller than if they were aligned closely, making them appear closer together in the sky than they actually are. This effect can be predicted and measured using orbital calculations, allowing astronomers to estimate the apparent conjunction distance for specific planetary alignments.",
      "source": "target",
